<h3 class="comments-header" style="color: #000!important; margin: 7px 0px;">Previous Discussion</h3> 

                     
                              <div class="comments-content">
                              
                                       <div id="comments"></div><div id="disqus_thread"></div>
            <div style="display:none;" id="disqus_post_title">Coffee and Cream Risotto</div>
            <div style="display:none;" id="disqus_post_message"><img alt="Coffee and Cream Risotto" src="http://www.treehugger.com/gwg-coffee-risotto-10.jpg" width="468" height="312" class="mt-image-none" style="" /><em>Photos by <a href="http://www.flickr.com/photos/jaymiheimbuch/sets/72157626053393551/">Jaymi Heimbuch</a></em>

It wasn't until I developed this <a href="http://www.treehugger.com/files/2011/09/vegetarian-french-onion-soup-made-with-coffee.php">French onion soup recipe made with coffee</a> that I realized just how much fun it is to cook with the seed. Sure, I have used it before, I add a dash of it to my <a href="http://www.treehugger.com/files/2011/04/cocoa-and-black-bean-brownies-with-raspberry-sauce.php">black bean brownies</a> which are simply divine. But now we're <em>really</em> cooking! Enjoy this dessert risotto with a white Port, preferably one with caramel notes. </div>
